## End-to-end flow (how it works)

1. Frontend calls POST /api/create-checkout-session with product_id and variant_id.
2. Backend calls Lemon Squeezy API `POST /v1/checkout_sessions` using the API key and returns the session URL to the frontend [Lemon Squeezy API docs](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/api).
3. Frontend calls `LemonSqueezy.Url.Open(url)` to open the hosted checkout overlay (overlay has nested Stripe iframes) [Lemon.js docs](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/lemonjs) and [checkout overlay docs](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/checkout/checkout-overlay).
4. Lemon Squeezy processes the payment in test or live mode; after order creation it sends an `order_created` webhook to your webhook endpoint with `X-Signature` header — verify signature using HMAC-SHA256 of the raw request body and your signing secret [Signing requests](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/webhooks/signing-requests).


## Testing procedures

1. Test Mode (in Lemon Squeezy dashboard): use `test_` API keys and test card numbers; test mode simulates full checkout behavior [Test Mode docs](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/getting-started/test-mode).

2. Simulate webhooks from the Lemon Squeezy dashboard in Test Mode to exercise your webhook code (you can replay events or simulate new ones) [Simulate webhook events docs](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/webhooks/simulate-webhook-events).

3. Local webhook testing using a tunnel (ngrok / Cloudflare tunnel): expose your local webhook endpoint and set that URL in the Lemon Squeezy webhook configuration; then trigger a simulated webhook from the dashboard. This verifies signature verification behavior against real Lemon Squeezy payloads [Webhooks guide](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/guides/developer-guide/webhooks).

4. Unit test the signature verification logic: create a small test script that computes the HMAC exactly as your server does and POSTs the payload with the `X-Signature` header to your local endpoint. Example (Node or Python) — Python example below:

```python
# test_send_webhook.py
import hmac
import hashlib
import requests

secret = 'your_test_signing_secret'
payload = b'{"meta":{"event_name":"order_created"},"data":{"id":1}}'
digest = hmac.new(secret.encode('utf-8'), payload, hashlib.sha256).hexdigest()
headers = {'Content-Type': 'application/json', 'X-Signature': digest}
resp = requests.post('https://your-tunnel-url/api/webhooks/order-created', data=payload, headers=headers)
print(resp.status_code, resp.text)
```

5. End-to-end browser tests (Playwright): because Lemon’s checkout overlay uses cross-origin iframes (and nested Stripe frames), use Playwright's frameLocator to interact with the overlay and nested frames (example below). Playwright example adapted for one-time purchase happy path:

```ts
// playwright/specs/checkout.spec.ts
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test'

test('one-time purchase happy path', async ({ page }) => {
  const testEmail = `buyer+${Date.now()}@example.com`
  await page.goto('http://localhost:5173')
  await page.getByRole('button', { name: /buy now/i }).click()

  // Lemon overlay iframe is cross-origin; locate it by 'src*="lemonsqueezy.com"'
  const overlay = page.frameLocator('iframe[src*="lemonsqueezy.com"]')
  await overlay.getByLabel(/email/i).fill(testEmail)

  // nested stripe iframe for card fields
  const stripe = overlay.frameLocator('iframe[src*="js.stripe.com"]')
  await stripe.locator('[name="cardnumber"]').fill('4242424242424242')
  await stripe.locator('[name="exp-date"]').fill('1230')
  await stripe.locator('[name="cvc"]').fill('123')

  await overlay.getByLabel(/name on card/i).fill('Test Buyer')
  await overlay.getByRole('button', { name: /pay/i }).click()

  await expect(overlay.getByText(/thank you|order confirmed/i)).toBeVisible({ timeout: 30000 })
})
```

Reference and notes: Playwright guidance and nested iframe handling described in third-party guides and Lemon checkout overlay docs [Playwright guide for Lemon Squeezy checkout](https://assrt.ai/t/how-to-test-lemon-squeezy-checkout) and [Checkout overlay docs](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/checkout/checkout-overlay).


## API key & webhook secret setup — where to get them

- API keys: Create API keys in Lemon Squeezy dashboard under Settings → API. Use keys starting with `test_` for Test Mode and live keys for production [Getting started / API](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/guides/developer-guide/getting-started).
- Webhook signing secret: When creating a webhook in the dashboard you are given (or can create) a signing secret — save this value securely; it is used to verify the `X-Signature` header [Webhooks guide & Signing requests](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/guides/developer-guide/webhooks) [Signing requests](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/webhooks/signing-requests).


## API key & webhook security best practices

- Never commit API keys or signing secrets to source control; use environment variables or a secrets manager [Getting started / API](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/guides/developer-guide/getting-started) and general API key best-practices [Akeyless article](https://www.akeyless.io/blog/power-of-api-keys).
- Keep keys scoped to the minimum permissions required (least privilege) and rotate regularly; revoke compromised keys immediately [API key management practices](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/guides/developer-guide/getting-started).
- Use HTTPS for all endpoints (Lemon Squeezy sends webhooks over HTTPS) [API docs require HTTPS](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/api).
- Verify webhook authenticity using the HMAC-SHA256 signature and the raw request body; reject requests with invalid signatures [Signing requests docs](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/webhooks/signing-requests).
- Store signing secrets in a secure store (Secrets Manager, Vault) in production instead of plain .env files; rotate periodically [general webhooks security guidance](https://stytch.com/blog/webhooks-security-best-practices).


## Common pitfalls and how to avoid them (with fixes)

1. Signature mismatches because the server hashed a parsed/JSON-stringified body instead of the raw request body.
   - Fix: Use the raw bytes of the incoming request to compute HMAC-SHA256 with your webhook secret and use timing-safe compare (`hmac.compare_digest`) [Signing requests](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/webhooks/signing-requests) and community troubleshooting [Stack Overflow example](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/78390848/lemonsqueezy-webhook-x-signature-returns-invalid-every-time).

2. Webhook POST converted to GET due to trailing-slash redirects (common in some frameworks like Django).
   - Fix: Ensure your webhook URL exactly matches the configured webhook (including trailing slash) or configure the router to accept both; avoid redirects so the original POST is preserved [community issue discussion](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/78058659/lemonsqueezy-webhook-requests-coming-through-as-get-instead-of-post-why).

3. CORS issues when frontend calls backend directly from browser.
   - Fix: Put sensitive operations (creating checkout sessions) on the server-side and enable CORS only for trusted origins. Use FastAPI's CORS middleware in dev with explicit origins and tighten in prod [Next.js guide & CORS guidance](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/guides/tutorials/nextjs-saas-billing).

4. Forgetting to use test_* API keys in Test Mode causing unexpected live charges.
   - Fix: Use the dashboard's Test Mode and `test_` keys while developing; test card numbers are provided for test mode [Test Mode docs & test cards](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/getting-started/test-mode).

5. Trying to interact with checkout if Lemon.js hasn't loaded or using an incorrect selector for overlay iframe.
   - Fix: Ensure Lemon.js script is loaded (defer or dynamic load), check `window.LemonSqueezy` before calling `Url.Open`, and fallback to full-page redirect if overlay API is not available [Lemon.js using with frameworks](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/lemonjs/using-with-frameworks-libraries) and overlay docs [checkout overlay](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/checkout/checkout-overlay).


## Practical debugging checklist (quick)

- Confirm API key is set and accessible to the FastAPI process (`LEMONSQUEEZY_API_KEY`) [Getting started](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/guides/developer-guide/getting-started).
- Verify `create-checkout-session` returns `{ "url": "https://..." }` and try opening that URL manually.
- Expose webhook endpoint (ngrok) and simulate webhook from dashboard; verify 200 and server logs for `order_created` [Simulate webhook events docs](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/webhooks/simulate-webhook-events).
- If webhook signature invalid: log raw request body and computed HMAC hex digest to compare against header (don’t store secrets in logs long-term) [Signing requests](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/webhooks/signing-requests).


## Minimal local run instructions (dev quickstart)

1. Create a Python venv and install the pinned packages:

```bash
python -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
pip install lemonsqueezy==0.2.0 fastapi==0.133.1 uvicorn==0.41.0 httpx==0.28.1 python-dotenv==1.2.2
```

2. Create `.env` from `.env.example` and fill keys (use test keys for dev) [Getting started / Test Mode](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/getting-started/test-mode).

3. Start backend:

```bash
uvicorn server:app --reload --host 127.0.0.1 --port 8000
```

4. Start frontend (example with Vite or CRA) and open http://localhost:5173 (set FRONTEND_ORIGIN accordingly) and click Buy.

5. Expose local backend for webhook testing with ngrok (or similar) and register that URL in Lemon Squeezy webhook settings; then trigger a test purchase or simulate webhook in dashboard [Simulate webhooks docs](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/webhooks/simulate-webhook-events).


## Quick reference links (inline where used above)
- Lemon Squeezy API: https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/api
- Webhook signing: https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/webhooks/signing-requests
- Lemon.js docs: https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/lemonjs
- Test Mode & test cards: https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/getting-started/test-mode
- Simulate webhook events: https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/webhooks/simulate-webhook-events


## Final notes (practical tips)

- Use test mode and `test_` API keys until you are confident in your end-to-end tests [Test Mode docs](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/help/getting-started/test-mode).
- Log webhook receipts (timestamp, event name, delivery id) to enable replay/debugging, but never log secrets or full card details (PCI sensitive) [webhooks and PCI considerations; Lemon Squeezy handles PCI on their side] [Webhooks guide](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/guides/developer-guide/webhooks).
- Keep your webhook endpoint idempotent — process incoming `order_created` events in a way that avoids double-granting if a webhook is retried; store event IDs you’ve handled [webhook best-practices guidance](https://docs.lemonsqueezy.com/guides/developer-guide/webhooks).

